1.1 Schach-Aktiv

I have dedicated the two following studies to Michael Ehn. Michael is a leading chess historian and author of many marvelous chess books. He has run the chess shop Schach und Spiele in Vienna over three decades. Whenever I have been visiting Vienna in recent years, I had the pleasure of meeting Michael in his shop. I hope Michael will continue his chess activities, and I am looking forward to his publications in the future.

GBR: =0007.11h8d1 FEN: 2N4K/8/8/4Pp1n/8/8/7n/3k4 w - - 0 1

Ng4 f1=N Tree knights win against one but 8. Nf6! and stalemate or an exchange of a pair of knights follows 1/2-1/2.

Harolds comments for the two studies in the provisional award:

It is a pity that the study starts with BTM, but it is not really disturbing here. All lines are crystal cleaar. This is a very good castling study!

Before the award candidates were checked for possible anticipations, I assumed 6 bishop sacrifices (of which 2 in sublines) on different squares was a task record and hence it opted for a good spot in the award. I did recall a study by Ornstein, version by Timman (#023216), and that happened to have also 4+2 B-sacs. It has a similar matrix, but with the bishops running on white squares. In total 16 studies were found with 4 B-sacs or more in the main line. But the record holder is Hoch (#052812) that has 10 B-scas on 8 different squares, with 4 B-sacs in sublines. Moreover, its setting is very economical.
